From 49233fad23922b4f625e87d6c4838de99287aa97 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: 0thernet <ben@substrate.run>
Date: Sun, 5 Jul 2026 11:10:34 -0400
Subject: [PATCH] feat(harness): emit action.invalid events for tool calls that
 fail validation
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

When the model emits a tool call that fails validation before execution
— an unknown tool name or unparsable/schema-invalid input — the call is
deliberately excluded from `actions.requested` and `action.result`, so
it vanished from the event stream entirely. Consumers could not observe
or measure invalid calls even though the model-facing retry loop was
already handling them.

The harness now emits a new `action.invalid` stream event for each such
call, carrying:

- `callId`, `toolName`, `turnId`, `stepIndex`, `sequence`
- `reason`: `"no-such-tool"` (unknown tool name) or `"invalid-input"`
  (unparsable JSON or input that failed the tool's schema)
- `errorText`: the AI SDK's validation error message
- `input`: the raw input when it is JSON-serializable

Emission happens on both passes — the streaming pass (invalid chunk on
the full stream) and the post-step pass (invalid entries in the step's
`toolCalls`) — deduped by call ID via a shared set, since the SDK can
surface an invalid call in either or both places.

The event deliberately ignores `excludedActionToolNames`: that exclusion
governs how valid calls are projected (e.g. HITL tools surface on
`input.requested` instead), while an invalid call has no other lifecycle
event and should stay observable for every tool.

Model-facing behavior is unchanged: the AI SDK still feeds the
validation error back to the model, which may retry on the next step.

Signed-off-by: 0thernet <ben@substrate.run>
